Derived Variables

There is likely to be a relationship between residual.sugar and acid. The more residual.sugar is present, the more acid is required to balance it. So it makes sense to have a variable with SugarToAcid. SugarToAcid is a the ratio of residual.sugar variable to the fixed.acidity variable. The volatile.acidity measurement is an indicator of spoilage so it was not considered. The balance of salt to sugar is also likely to have an effect on the taste of wine. So another derivied varialble will be SugarToSalt(Chlorides).

wine$SugarToAcid <- wine$residual.sugar / wine$fixed.acidity
wine$SugarToSalt <- wine$residual.sugar / wine$chlorides

Bivariate Analysis

Lets try plotting quality versus the the input variables. This may be a dead end but it is hard to make inferences from the ggpairs plot.
Citric acid has a fairly strong correlation with fixed.acidity. It must be remembered that many wines in the sample have no citric acid. So the influence of citric acid is hard to quantify.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

You can say that on average for a given quality, as the volatile acidity increases the quality decreases.

Its not posbile to make any inferences about fixed acidity adn quality.

Its not clear from the plots what influence citric acid has on wine quality. It could be argued that as wine alcohol content increases teh quality tends to rise. We are lacking enough data points for certain quality values to definitely make this claim.

Its not possible to make claims of residual sugars influence on quality.
Most values lie between 1.5 and 3 and in that range all quality values are represented.

Its not clear what influence chloride content has on wine. Most values are in a narrow range and in tha range all quality values are present.

Its not clear how free sulfur dioxide affects quality. There are ranges of values in each quality value.

Its not clear how total sulfur.dioxide affects quality. There are ranges of value for each quality value.

You could make a claim that there is a correlation between sulphates and wine quality. All of the higher quality values have progressively lower minimum sulphate levels.

THere is a very weak correlation between density and wine quality. THe lower quality wines have a higher density on average than the higher quality wines.

There is on clear relationship between pH and wine quality.

THere is no clear relationship between the SugarToAcid ratio and wine quality.

THere is a very weak trend that the higher the SugarToSalt ratio is the higher the wine quality.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

No.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship was the inverse relationship between volatile acidity and wine quality.
